commText: Warner and Fraser-McGurk are at the crease. Warner is on strike. Swapnil Singh will open the attack
Swapnil Singh to Warner, 1 run, full on off-stump, eased down the ground to long-on for one
Swapnil Singh to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, Fraser-McGurk needs absolutely no sighters! Floated up full on off-stump, Fraser-McGurk planted his foot forward and smoked it clean over long-off
Swapnil Singh to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, flatter delivery outside off, slapped away to wide long-off
Swapnil Singh to Warner, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Swapnil Singh to Warner, out Caught by Will Jacks!! Warner goes cheaply on his return! Early wicket for RCB and that's exactly what they needed. Full on off-stump, was there to be hit and Warner leant in looking to slog-sweep, hit it fairly well but hit it too straight, Jacks at long-on moved to his left and took it easily inside the ropes. Not the start DC were after. Warner c Will Jacks b Swapnil Singh 1(2)
Abishek Porel, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Swapnil Singh to Abishek Porel, 1 run, full on off-stump, knocked back towards the bowler who dives to his left and fails to stop it cleanly
Swapnil Singh to Fraser-McGurk, no run, tossed up full and outside off, Fraser-McGurk leant in and had a big swing across the line, he missed
Mohammed Siraj, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
RCB review. Lot of confusion here as the appeal lbw first came from Kohli at mid-off and then everyone else joined in

Siraj to Abishek Porel, 1 run, review lost! Was a beautiful inswinging yorker on middle, Abishek Porel jammed his bat down and it went down towards third man, the third umpire had one look at determined it was off the bat, Kohli and co are not at all happy with that
Siraj to Fraser-McGurk, no run, length delivery on middle, Fraser-McGurk gets right behind it with a solid block
Siraj to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, here's another clean strike! Full and straight on middle, riught in the slot, Fraser-McGurk cleared his front-leg and lofted it through the line and over long-on
Siraj has a slip in
Siraj to Fraser-McGurk, no run, length delivery outside off, swings away and Fraser-McGurk slogs and misses

Siraj to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, outside edge and four! Juicy full-toss outside off, Fraser-McGurk stood still and had a big swing at this again, got a thick outside edge that raced away past Green at slip
Third man comes in and long-on moves out

Siraj to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, Fraser-McGurk is off to another flier! Length delivery angling into the pads, Fraser-McGurk backed away to make some room and carved it up and over cover, wasn't too far from the man but it's another boundary
Yash Dayal, left-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Yash Dayal to Abishek Porel, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Yash Dayal to Abishek Porel, out Caught by Ferguson!! A wicket off his very first ball for Dayal! Length delivery on off-stump, just a hint of shape away and it got big on Abishek Porel as he looked to heave it away into the leg-side, bat turned in his hand as it caught the top half and it lobbed up, Ferguson ran in from cover and took it easily. So two early wickets for RCB while Fraser-McGurk smashes it around at the other end. Abishek Porel c Ferguson b Yash Dayal 2(3)
Shai Hope, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, THATS OUT!! Run Out!!

Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, out Fraser-McGurk Run Out!! That's the most unfortunate way to go for Fraser-McGurk! RCB are absolutely ecstatic, they can't believe their luck. Was full and shaping into middle, Shai Hope creamed the drive straight back and Dayal stuck his left-hand out, it brushed his fingers before slamming into the stumps at the other end and Fraser-McGurk was just a touch slow in getting back into his crease. A dream start for RCB now. They've got three in no time. Fraser-McGurk run out (Yash Dayal) 21(8) [4s-2 6s-2]
Two slips now
Kumar Kushagra, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, no run, full and just outside off, shapes in nicely, Shai Hope looks to drive again and pulls out of the shot to let it go
A third slip comes in

Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, FOUR, edged and four! Maybe RCB can bring a gully too now, beautiful delivery this, on a length on middle, just kept angling away and Shai Hope closed the face looking to clip it into the leg-side, caught the leading edge and raced away past third slip
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, no run, length delivery on middle, bunted towards mid-on
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, no run, full and slanting across just outside off, shapes away too as Shai Hope shoulders arms, what an over for RCB! Couldn't have asked for much more
Two slips in place
Siraj to Kushagra, 2 runs, full and straight on middle, drifts into the pads and Kushagra clips it away past square leg for a couple, wrong line to bowl with two slips in place
Most sixes in the Powerplay in one IPL season 24 - Abhishek Sharma (SRH, 2024) 22 - Travis Head (SRH, 2024) 22 - Sanath Jayasuriya (MI, 2008) 21 - Jake Fraser-McGurk (DC, 2024)
Siraj to Kushagra, no run, good length delivery on middle, Kushagra prods forward to block and is struck on the thigh pad as it nips in a shade
Siraj to Kushagra, THATS OUT!! Lbw!!

Siraj to Kushagra, out Lbw!! That's absolutely plumb lbw! Full and angling into middle, just nipped back a touch and Kushagra played all around it, left a big gap between bat and pad as he looked to push it back, it beat the bat and front-pad, hit the back pad and the umpire had no hesitation in giving that out. It just keeps getting better for RCB. The Capitals are in deep trouble. Oh how badly they would've liked to have Rishabh Pant in such a situation. Kushagra lbw b Siraj 2(3)
Axar Patel, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Siraj to Axar, no run, full and outside off, driven straight to cover
Siraj to Axar, no run, banged in short on off-stump, gets it about head-high and it zips through to the keeper
Siraj to Axar, no run, very full on off-stump, squeezed out towards point
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, FOUR, that's a beautiful shot! Full and shaping into off-stump, Shai Hope pressed forward and into a lovely extra cover drive, sublime timing and placement
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, no run, full on off-stump, knocked towards cover
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, FOUR, that's lovely timing again! Length delivery on the pads, Shai Hope tucked it away towards square leg, found the gap and timed it so sweetly again
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, FOUR, through the covers once more! Pitched up full and outside off, Shai Hope pressed forward and carved it through the covers for another boundary
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, no run, good length delivery on middle, Shai Hope hangs back and blocks it towards mid-off
Yash Dayal to Shai Hope, 1 run, good length delivery on off-stump, eased down towards point for one
Still a slip in place
Siraj to Shai Hope, 1 run, good length delivery on off-stump, Shai Hope hangs back and just drops it into the off-side towards gully for a quick single
Siraj to Axar, FOUR, into the gap! Length delivery outside off, too much width on offer and Axar punched it away through point, easy pickings
Siraj to Axar, no run, good length delivery on off-stump, Axar looks to drive it back and gets a thick inside edge onto the pads

Siraj to Axar, 2 runs, oh dear, misfield, full and just outside off, Axar drove it towards cover, was a shade early through it and the man at cover let it straight through, did well to track it down after
Siraj to Axar, no run, full on middle, driven straight back to the bowler
Siraj to Axar, FOUR, that's a great shot! Full and just outside off, in the slot and Axar drilled it straight back, mid-off was quite wide and it raced down the ground
Teams losing most wickets in the Powerplay in IPL 2024 27 - DC 25 - MI 20 - RCB 20 - PBKS 20 - LSG

Highlights (Overs 1-6) - Swapnil gets the big wicket of Warner in the opening over - Fraser-McGurk gets going as DC smash 15 off the 2nd over - Dayal gets Porel first ball - Freaky run-out off Fraser-McGurk leaves DC 3 down inside 2.3 overs - Siraj nips out Kushagra lbw for 2 - Hope hits Dayal for three boundaries off his 2nd over - Siraj goes for 11 in the last over of powerplay
Karn Sharma, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack
Karn Sharma to Shai Hope, 1 run, tossed up full on leg-stump, Shai Hope clears his front leg and pushes it down the ground to long-off
Karn Sharma to Axar, 1 run, length delivery on middle, worked away towards mid-wicket for a single
Karn Sharma to Shai Hope, 1 run, tossed up full on off-stump, driven out towards deep extra cover
Karn Sharma to Axar, 1 run, length delivery on off-stump, Axar runs down the pitch and hacks it away towards long-on, gets lucky because he times it terribly, lands well short of the man running in
Karn Sharma to Shai Hope, 1 run, flatter delivery outside off, slapped out towards deep cover
Karn Sharma to Axar, FOUR, that's a poor delivery! Dragged down short on middle, Axar pressed back and pulled it away firmly into the gap at deep square leg, good finish to the over
Timeout. RCB have gotten off to a great start but they've got to be careful not to let DC get away with a big partnership here. They've still got Stubbs in the shed who's in great form.
Lockie Ferguson, right-arm fast, comes into the attack
Ferguson to Shai Hope, 2 runs, I0$ pitched full and wide of off, Hope leans into the drive and hits it to the right of sweeper cover
Ferguson to Shai Hope, 1 run, a bit too full around off at 148ks, Hope jams the drive to the left of cover and a slight misfield enables a quick single
Ferguson to Axar, 1 run, pulls his length back and keeps it just outside off at I0$, Axar opens the bat face and drops it on the off-side for a quick single
Ferguson to Shai Hope, 2 runs, I0$ length ball angled in towards middle and leg, Hope whips it to the left of deep mid-wicket and a sliding stop by Swapnil prevents the boundary
Ferguson to Shai Hope, 1 run, takes the pace off and goes full and wide at I0$, Hope gets a thick outside edge on the drive fine of third man
Ferguson to Axar, leg byes, 1 run, skiddy length delivery angled in from round the wicket, Axar misses the flick and theg ball rolls off the thigh pad towards square leg
Cameron Green, right-arm medium, comes into the attack
Green to Axar, FOUR, Green overpitches first ball and Axar clears his front leg before thumping this back over the bowler's head for a much-needed boundary
Green to Axar, 2 runs, comes running down the wicket and slashes the I0$ length delivery to the right of backward point
Green to Axar, 1 run, full and pitched outside leg, Axar looks to nudge leg-side and gets a thick leading edge rolling into the covers
Green to Shai Hope, no run, length delivery with a hint of extra bounce at I0$ Hope looks to defend and gets it off the splice of the bat
Green to Shai Hope, 2 runs, hops on the back foot and works the I0$ length delivery off the pads behind square on the leg-side
Green to Shai Hope, wide, Green unfurls the bumper but that's too high and down leg as Hope ducks under it
Green to Shai Hope, no run, good length on and around off at I0$, punched straight to cover

Ferguson to Axar, FOUR, uses all of Ferguson's pace does the DC skipper. Hangs back, opens the bat face really late against this I0$ back of a length and guides it really fine, beating the fielder at third man to his right
Ferguson to Axar, 1 run, once again opens the bat face to steer a I0$ short of length delivery square on the off-side
Ferguson to Shai Hope, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ferguson to Shai Hope, out Caught by Karn Sharma!! Karn Sharma takes a terrific catch and the RCB fielders swarm around to acknowledge the brilliance of that catch. A relatively high (slower ball) full toss from Ferguson and Hope had dragged it off the thick inside half. The bottom hand came off the blade as well and had no control over the shot. Karn Sharma was at deep mid-wicket and he came sprinting in to his left before pulling off a well-timed slide to pluck the ball out of thin air. The best part was that he had another fielder (Swapnil from long-on) in his vision bustling right into him, but Karn did well to maintain his composure and completed the catch sans any fuss. Shai Hope c Karn Sharma b Ferguson 29(23) [4s-4]
Tristan Stubbs, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Ferguson to Tristan Stubbs, no run, back of a length just outside off, Stubbs hops and defends
Ferguson to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, fuller on off, driven down to long-on
Ferguson to Axar, no run, blocked from the crease
Green to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, back of a length outside off, Stubbs angles his bat and steers it fine of third man
Green to Axar, 1 run, shorter and wider of off, stabbed away to deep cover
Green to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, full outside off at I0$, lures Stubbs into a drive and gets a thick outside edge rolling down to third man
Green to Axar, no run, I0$ back of a length on the stumps, Axar chops it to backward point
Green to Axar, no run, hops and cuts the short ball to Kohli at backward point
Green to Axar, THATS OUT!! Run Out!!

Green to Axar, out Tristan Stubbs Run Out!! There's no stopping RCB. They are taking every opportunity to try and close this game out in hope of a big margin. This was gently knocked down the pitch to the left of Axar and Tristan Stubbs came rushing down the pitch in search of a quick single. Cam Green was alert and made sure he chased the ball from his followthrough. Picks the ball calmly and pings the stumps direct with a brilliant direct hit. Stubbs was long way down the track and had no chance of getting back. Tristan Stubbs run out (Green) 3(4)
Karn Sharma [1.0-0-9-0] is back into the attack
Rasikh Dar Salam, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Karn Sharma to Rasikh Salam, no run, tossed up just outside off, Rasikh Salam gets forward and drives into the off-side
Karn Sharma to Rasikh Salam, 1 run, driven to the left of the bowler and Karn Sharma fumbles on the slide to concede a single
Karn Sharma to Axar, SIX, smoked away into the mid-wicket orbit. Floaty full delivery on the stumps, Axar gets down on one knee and belts the slogsweep for an 80-metre maximum
Karn Sharma to Axar, 2 runs, advances and slices the drive to the left of sweeper cover
Karn Sharma to Axar, 1 run, flatter on leg stump, Axar drops it into the leg-side for a quick single
Karn Sharma to Rasikh Salam, no run, slower and fuller on the stumps, pushed back to the bowler off the front foot
Will Jacks, right-arm off break, comes into the attack

Will Jacks to Axar, SIX, just enough to beat the fielder. Will Jacks loops it up just outside off, Axar stays low and gets enough contact on the slogsweep to beat the leaping Green at deep mid-wicket to his left
Will Jacks to Axar, 1 run, forced away into the covers
Will Jacks to Rasikh Salam, 1 run, comes down the track and cuts the quicker delivery to the left of sweeper cover
Will Jacks to Axar, 1 run, Axar charges down the track and heaves the flatter delivery to the right of long-on
Will Jacks to Rasikh Salam, 1 run, floated full outside off, Rasikh slices the drive to the left of deep cover
Will Jacks to Axar, SIX, fifty up for the skipper. His second this season and 3rd overall. He gets under the teasing full delivery and clubs it many-a-mile over long-on with a stamp of authority...
Lockie Ferguson [2.0-0-13-1] is back into the attack

Ferguson to Rasikh Salam, FOUR, sloppy work from Siraj results in a boundary. Rasikh came hustling down the track and sliced the length delivery to the left of sweeper cover, Siraj came running in but made contact with the ropes before completing the dive...
Ferguson to Rasikh Salam, 1 run, tucked away off the hip to fine leg
Ferguson to Axar, 1 run, short of length on the stumps, Axar hangs back and nudges into the leg-side for a quick single
Ferguson to Rasikh Salam, 1 run, I0$ skiddy short of length delivery outside off, Rasikh opens the bat face and steers it to the left of deep backward point
Ferguson to Axar, 1 run, full and drifting into the pads at I0$, Axar clips it down to fine leg
Ferguson to Rasikh Salam, no run, full and just outside off at I0$, Rasikh opens the bat face and forces the drive to cover
DC need 64 off the last 6 overs
Cameron Green [2.0-0-13-0] is back into the attack
Green to Axar, no run, Axar looks to heave leg-side and misses, was hurried into the shot and got hit around the hip
Green to Axar, 1 run, in the air and safe! I0$ short outside off, Axar slogs and to his delight, the top-edge drops well short of the incoming deep mid-wicket fielder who collects it on the bounce
Green to Rasikh Salam, no run, Rasikh advances and looks to slam one on the off-side but gets beaten by the I0$ length delivery outside off
Green to Rasikh Salam, 1 run, jumps inside the crease and tucks the I0$ length delivery behind square on the leg-side
Green to Axar, 1 run, opens the bat face and guides the I0$ back of a length delivery down to third man
Green to Rasikh Salam, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Green to Rasikh Salam, out Caught by Will Jacks!! The 37-run partnership comes to an end. Slower ball from Cam Green. Neither full nor short. Rasikh gave himself ample room outside off searching for a loft down the ground and instead chips it off toe towards Will Jacks at long-on. Rasikh Salam c Will Jacks b Green 10(12) [4s-1]

Summary (Overs 7-15) > Hope and Axar look to stabilize DC > Hope falls to a Ferguson full-toss in the 10th over > Axar carries on strong and gets some crucial boundaries > Stubbs runs himself out in the 12th over > Axar brings up fifty but starts running out of partners

Timeout! DC need 61 off the last 5 overs. The required rate definitely doesn't pose a threat, but the wickets column certainly does if you are DC fan. As for RCB, their only and only focus will be to get rid of Axar in the next 2-3 overs...

Kuldeep Yadav, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Yash Dayal to Axar, no run, I0$ high full toss just outside off, Axar looks to heave leg-side and gets a thick inside edge that slams straight into the inside thigh of his right leg...
Yash Dayal to Axar, no run, room on offer outside off, Axar cuts but can't beat backward point
Yash Dayal to Axar, wide, slower full delivery sprayed well wide of off at I0$, Axar shoulders arms
Yash Dayal to Axar, no run, another slower delivery bowled full outside off, Axar backed away a little and that had made it difficult for him to fetch. Well inside the guideline that one...
Yash Dayal to Axar, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Yash Dayal to Axar, out Caught by du Plessis!! That should be the game for RCB. Yash Dayal bowls the seam-up length delivery wide of off, Axar looked for a big swipe and got a thick top-edge behind square on the off-side. Faf, at backward point, calls for it early and runs back to complete the catch with an awkward tumble. Axar c du Plessis b Yash Dayal 57(39) [4s-5 6s-3]

Yash Dayal to Mukesh Kumar, 1 run, full around off, driven down to long-on

Green to Kuldeep Yadav, no run, I0$ short of length delivery on off, punched back to the bowler

Ferguson to Mukesh Kumar, 1 run, I0$ short on the stumps, Mukesh heaves and chips it off the thick inside half over mid-on

Yash Dayal [3.0-0-20-2] is back into the attack
Yash Dayal to Kuldeep Yadav, THATS OUT!! Bowled!!

Yash Dayal to Kuldeep Yadav, out Bowled!! Kuldeep makes room looking to go down the ground and misses, Yash Dayal did well not to bowl it too full and kept the line around middle and off. Timber. Game over. RCB win by 47 runs and move to the 5th spot. Kuldeep Yadav b Yash Dayal 6(10)

23:07 local, 17:37 GMT: All those dropped catches and misfields certainly came back to haunt DC. Although they did well to pull things back in the back end of RCB's innings, they needed a bit more than luck during the chase after losing 4 wickets inside 4 overs. Despite losing Warner off the opening over, Fraser-McGurk continued to bat on his merry way but a freakish run-out (palmed over the bowler in his followthrough) in the 3rd over put a huge dent which DC failed to recover. Hope and Axar stitched a 56-run stand for the 5th wicket, and, unfortunately for DC, they lost the wickets of Hope and Stubbs in quick succession to make thigs that much more difficult for them. Axar's lone battle only helped in bringing down the defeat margin as RCB romped home to keep their playoff hopes alive. Hang around for the post-match comments...

Axar Patel: Dropped catches hurt us. Could've restricted them to 150. When you lose four wickets in powerplay, you're always chasing the game. 160-170 would've been a par score. Pitch was two-paced. Some were skidding, some were holding. When your main players are run out and you lose four in powerplay, you're chasing the game. Anything can happen, but haven't thought that far ahead.

Lockie Ferguson: We’ve all been working really hard throughout the tournament. Even when we were losing, it was all very even, we were still enjoying ourselves, we knew that things would go right soon. The batters did extremely well, it was gripping a bit more than normal. Looking forward to a few days off and then taking on Chennai. Can be challenging bowling here, been great working with Griffith (bowling coach). Makes it easy when we take wickets throughout.
Most consecutive wins for RCB 7 in 2011 (runners-up) 5 in 2009 (runners-up) 5 in 2016 (runners-up) 5* in 2024 4 in 2010 (playoffs) 4 in 2021 (playoffs)
- The last instance of RCB successfully defending a target in a night game at Chinnaswamy was against PBKS in 2019.
- 140 all-out is the lowest innings score for DC and the lowest against RCB this season.
Stats by Roshan Gede

Faf du Plessis | RCB skipper: Brilliant, we put some good performances and really pleased. 1st half of the season, things didn't quite come together and from that batting perspective and bowling perspective we have been able to put it together now. Sometimes people talk about match-ups and all, but as a left hander with the ball spinning in, you hope that works out sometimes and he's (Swapnil) done brilliantly for us. Lot of work has gone behind the scenes, and we are getting it right and I feel there is a lot more variety in our bowling now and Yash and Lockie have been exceptional the last few games. We wanna play a style of cricket, to be bold and put some performances together and keep going.

Cam Green | Player of the Match: Great game for our team. This year there has been so many high scores and there is little bit something there for the bowler and our bowlers were brilliant from the start. We identified that pace on is easy to play, Khaleel bowled a lot of off-cutters which were gripping and tough to target and we tried the same in our bowling. This is such a small ground and there is something in there for the bowlers which is good to see.

Battle of NRR: RCB will surpass CSK's run-rate if they win by 18 runs or more on May 18 (assuming they score 200 batting first). If the target is 201, they'll have to chase it down with roughly 11 balls remaining.

5th spot for RCB as their playoff hopes shine brighter with each passing day. Remember, no other team has won 5 on the bounce this season except RCB. Can they make it six on the bounce and sneak into the playoffs? A lot of things need to go their way for that to materialize. All of that for later, but locking horns tomorrow will be table-toppers KKR against GT in Ahmedabad. A must-win for GT. Meanwhile, a win for KKR will ensure a top-two finish for them. Lots at stake for both those sides as we draw curtains on the penultimate double-header of the season. On behalf of our ever-alert scorer Mukesh Gowda, and the comm duo of I0$, this is I1$ bidding goodbye on game 62. Cheers!!
